\section{Intersample Attention}{

With \code{attention_type} set to \code{"row"} or \code{"colrow"} (the default), SAINT attends over the rows of
the current batch. This has consequences that users must be aware of:
\itemize{
\item The prediction for an observation \strong{depends on which other observations are in its batch}.
Predictions therefore change when \code{batch_size} changes and when the row order changes.
\item A batch containing a single row degenerates: attention over one row reduces to a pass-through.
This can happen at prediction time for the last (incomplete) batch. Prefer a \code{batch_size} that
divides the number of rows to predict, or use \code{attention_type = "col"} if you need
row-independent predictions.
\item The learner warns at prediction time when \code{batch_size} is smaller than 8 and intersample
attention is active.
}

This is inherent to the architecture as published, not an implementation artefact. With
\code{attention_type = "col"} the network reduces to a standard feature-wise transformer and
predictions are independent across rows.
}

